<section id="closure-and-scope-chain-in-javascript" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="closure-and-scope-chain-in-javascript">Closure and Scope Chain in JavaScript</h2>
<p>Functions in JavaScript form closures. A closure refers to the <strong>combination of a function and the surrounding state in which the function was declared</strong>. This surrounding state, also called its lexical environment, consists of <strong>any local variables that were in scope at the time the closure was made</strong>. Here is an example:</p>
<div id="fig-makeadding" class="lightbox quarto-float quarto-figure quarto-figure-center anchored">
<figure class="quarto-float quarto-float-fig figure">
<div aria-describedby="fig-makeadding-caption-0ceaefa1-69ba-4598-a22c-09a6ac19f8ca">
<a href="img/makeAdding.png" class="lightbox" data-gallery="quarto-lightbox-gallery-1" title="Figure&nbsp;1: makeAdding() example"><img src="https://blog.prpr.one/posts/javascriptclosure/img/makeAdding.png" class="img-fluid figure-img"></a>
</div>
<figcaption class="quarto-float-caption-bottom quarto-float-caption quarto-float-fig" id="fig-makeadding-caption-0ceaefa1-69ba-4598-a22c-09a6ac19f8ca">
Figure&nbsp;1: <code>makeAdding()</code> example
</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p>Here, <code>add5</code> is a reference to the resulting function, created when the makeAdding function is executed, thus it has access to the lexical environment of the resulting function, which contains the first variable, making it available for use. The <code>first</code> variable is stored inside the <code>Scope[0]</code> closure with the returned function assigned to <code>add5</code>, on top of the Global scope.</p>
<p>So I came up with another understanding of closure, which is the ability to access a parent level scope from a child scope, even after the parent function has been terminated. The closure keeps its state between calls.</p>
